=C2=A0

With that in mind, I was even more surprised to see that Heritage Urban Art=
=E2=80=99s Instagram account on Friday morning had posted a celebratory pic=
ture of the team, flexing that the Retna sale had
made more than $2 million. By Saturday morning, the post had been taken dow=
n.

Also on Friday, Vulture posted its own version ( https://www.vulture.com/ar=
ticle/retna-stolen-graffiti-art-heritage-auctions.html?utm_campaign=3DWall+=
Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F2%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS=
+%282%2F2%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_te=
rm=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) of the same story Artnet wrote on Tuesday. In it,=
 Rachel Corbett explained Lewis=E2=80=99s version of events. He=E2=80=99d m=
issed two payments and believes he=E2=80=99d repaid the back rent,
only to have the sister of his original landlord raise her claim and refuse=
 to accept payment. To make matters worse, Lewis seems to have been in some=
 trouble with the law=E2=80=94locked up in the hoosegow, it seems=E2=80=94d=
uring the proceedings that ended up putting his works in the hands of his f=
ormer landlord. It had been the landlord conducting an abandoned property s=
ale through Heritage.

In Vulture=E2=80=99s story, Vartian said he was satisfied that
nothing unlawful was going on with the sale. =E2=80=9CHeritage wouldn=E2=80=
=99t be involved in anything if it was unlawful,=E2=80=9D he added. Fair en=
ough. But then why take down the Instagram post?

=C2=A0

On that note, I won=E2=80=99t say =E2=80=9Cgoodbye,=E2=80=9D but so long, u=
ntil Tuesday=E2=80=A6=C2=A0

