"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Compared with the rest of the year, January i=
s a relatively quiet
month for events around New York=E2=80=94with the exception of the New York=
 City Ballet=E2=80=99s annual Art Series. For the past 13 years, the compan=
y has commissioned a mid-career artist to create an installation for the Da=
vid H. Koch Theater=E2=80=99s promenade, and held three special performance=
s with discounted tickets. The program started as an audience development t=
ool, and has by all accounts been hugely successful: About half of those wh=
o buy tickets to the Art Series are brand new to NYCB.<br/><br/>The first
artist to participate in the series, in 2013, was <strong>Faile</strong>=E2=
=80=94followed by <strong>JR</strong>, <strong>Dustin Yellin</strong>, <str=
ong>Marcel Dzama</strong>, and<strong> Santtu Mustonen</strong>. In 2018, <=
strong>Geronimo</strong> filled the promenade with mirrored balloons; the f=
ollowing year, <strong>Shantell Martin</strong> created one of her signatur=
e black-and-white line paintings live onstage. In 2023, <strong>Lonneke Gor=
dijn</strong> and <strong>Ralph
Nauta</strong>=E2=80=99s Studio DRIFT installed their kinetic Shylights alo=
ng the ceiling. While some pieces remain on view around the theater buildin=
g, most of the works have been returned to the artists.<br/><br/></p><p sty=
le=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">This year, the company commissioned a ph=
otographer for the first time: <strong>Elizaveta Porodina</strong>, whose t=
heatrical, Technicolor images of NYCB dancers in motion are hanging from th=
e promenade ceiling on oversize sheer scrims, where they=E2=80=99ll
stay for the duration of the company=E2=80=99s winter season, ending March =
2. Each attendee at one of the Art Series performances receives a commemora=
tive postcard with one of Porodina=E2=80=99s images.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">I caught one of the Art Series performances on Friday night. The first =
ballet of the evening, <strong>Christopher Wheeldon</strong>=E2=80=99s <em>=
From You Within M</em>e, premiered last year, and features costumes and
backdrops by Alaska-born artist <strong>Kylie Manning</strong>, who is repr=
esented by Pace. (I spotted her in the audience with the gallery=E2=80=99s =
president, <strong>Samanthe Rubell</strong>.) The third, <em>Mystic Familia=
r</em>, was a world premiere by <strong>Justin Peck</strong>, featuring a b=
acklit abstract geometric backdrop by Arizona-born artist <strong>Eamon Ore=
-Giron</strong>, featured in this year=E2=80=99s Whitney Biennial and repre=
sented by James Cohan Gallery.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;
margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">The final Art Series p=
erformance is this Saturday, February 8. There are still a few tickets left=
=2E If you go, stay for the afterparty on the promenade.</p></div>
